<div id="review_3996598649" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3996598649" />
    <a title="Bruce Cowan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/134919028-bruce-cowan"><img alt="Bruce Cowan" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3996598649?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bruce Cowan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bruce Cowan" href="/user/show/134919028-bruce-cowan">Bruce Cowan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3996598649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14798152754537048492">I struggled with the book from the start. Even here it quotes General Wickham from the book. Having served from 98-15, I have a pretty good understanding of what Soldiers are willing to endure. The reality of it, is that technology has changed and we don’t have to ask them to do the same thing today. Ask any Soldier with time in one of the Remote Outposts in Afghanistan and they will give you a decent idea of what it’s like to hold a terrible position under fire. Another area was the brotherhood</span>
  <span id="freeText14798152754537048492" style="display:none">I struggled with the book from the start. Even here it quotes General Wickham from the book. Having served from 98-15, I have a pretty good understanding of what Soldiers are willing to endure. The reality of it, is that technology has changed and we don’t have to ask them to do the same thing today. Ask any Soldier with time in one of the Remote Outposts in Afghanistan and they will give you a decent idea of what it’s like to hold a terrible position under fire. Another area was the brotherhood, comrades is in the name and there was 13 or 16 pages on it. This is a large part of why you fight. Save your buddies. Having spent a few hours with some Medal of Honor Recipients they both shared the same idea of the Medal being for their lost brothers. I felt this was a misstep in title and short chapter. <br /><br />If you made it this far I will tell you that my complaints about the book are due to what McPherson had to work with. It is impossible for someone to understand the bond forged under fire. Especially a good historian working off of letters left behind, after 150 years or so. I for one never wrote home or called in later deployments. General Wickham was long gone before my time and I hate to discredit him, but I think he was wrong. It could be the era and war he was in, who knows. Troops always surprise you in the heat of battle and had that been General Odierno or Petraeus I would’ve taken it personal. You never know what you are capable of until you are asked to confront it. <br /><br />I do appreciate the effort that McPherson put in to this. He went through a lot of primary sources to tell why Soldiers of the Civil War fought. It has a place for college and civil war enthusiasts, because of its historical accuracy. I gave it a four because it is true scholarly work. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14798152754537048492" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


